  "prompt": "What is derivation Of E=mc^2?",
  "response": "The equation \\(E=mc^2\\) is one of the most famous equations in physics, derived from Albert Einstein's theory of special relativity. It relates energy (E) and mass (m) with \\(c\\) representing the speed of light in a vacuum (approximately \\(3 \\times 10^8\\) meters per second). The equation implies that mass can be converted into energy and vice versa, and it underpins much of modern physics.\n\n### Derivation Overview\n\nThe derivation of \\(E=mc^2\\) can be approached through different methods. A common and intuitive derivation comes from considering the properties of energy and momentum in special relativity. Here is a simplified version of the derivation:\n\n1. **Relativistic Momentum**:\n   - In classical mechanics, momentum \\(p\\) is defined as \\(p = mv\\) where \\(m\\) is mass and \\(v\\) is velocity. Einstein extended this concept into relativistic physics. The relativistic momentum is given by:\n     \\[\n     p = \\gamma mv\n     \\]\n     where \\(\\gamma = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - \\frac{v^2}{c^2}}}\\), and \\(c\\) is the speed of light.\n\n2. **Kinetic Energy**:\n   - The kinetic energy (KE) of an object is related to its motion. In classical mechanics, it's given by \\(\\text{KE} = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2\\). However, in relativity, the relationship changes as speeds approach the speed of light.\n   - The total energy \\(E\\) of an object moving at velocity \\(v\\) is given by the relation:\n     \\[\n     E = \\gamma mc^2\n     \\]\n   - When an object is at rest (when \\(v = 0\\)), the energy simplifies to \\(E_0 = mc^2\\), where \\(E_0\\) is the rest energy of the object.\n\n3. **Relation of Energy and Mass**:\n   - This equation, \\(E = \\gamma mc^2\\), shows that as the object approaches the speed of light, its energy increases more significantly due to the factor \\(\\gamma\\). \n\n4. **Rest Energy**:\n   - For an object at rest (where \\(v=0\\)), \\(\\gamma = 1\\) and thus:\n     \\[\n     E = mc^2\n     \\]\n   - This form indicates that the energy contained in a mass at rest is proportional to the mass itself and the square of the speed of light, demonstrating that mass itself is a concentrated form of energy.\n\n### Summary\n\nThus, \\(E=mc^2\\) arises logically from the principles of special relativity, linking mass and energy. It highlights the profound relationship where mass can be converted to energy, which has far-reaching implications in nuclear physics, astrophysics, and cosmology.",
